 of ministry","body":"He was ordained at Chatham (now Portland) on August 9, 1767 and remained its Congregational pastor until his death on November 17, 1811 — 44 years in the same pulpit. His gravestone records both: \"In the 68th year of his age, And 44th of his ministry; In morals, exemplary; In doctrine, uncorrupt; In reasoning, profound.\""},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Yale or Harvard? — the record says Yale","body":"EH, the Strong family book, and Yale archival records all confirm he graduated Yale 1763. The Native Northeast Portal biography states Harvard — this appears to be an error in that source. He served as Farmington Town Clerk 1764-67 immediately after graduation, before ordination."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"His granddaughter walked the Trail of Tears","body":"His daughter Sarah Strong married Judge John Ellsworth; their daughter Harriet Ellsworth married Ainsworth Blunt at Brainerd Mission, Tennessee, where they ministered to the Cherokees. When the forced removal came in 1838, Blunt accompanied the Cherokees on the Trail of Tears before illness forced him back from the Mississippi. He later became the first mayor of Dalton, Georgia."}],"education":[{"degree":"B.A.","notes":"EH, Strong family book (5345-8), and Yale archival collection all confirm Yale 1763. Native Northeast Portal biography states Harvard — this appears to be an error in that source. Sprague Annals of the American Pulpit vol. I pp. 651-3 contains a life sketch.","school_name":"Yale College","graduation_year":1763,"institution_id":"INST022"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Cyprian Strong","first_name":"Cyprian","last_name":"Strong","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://images.findagrave.com/photos/2016/99/18878632_1460208376.jpg?size=photos250"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1763"}],"landmarks":[],"artwor